The paper deals with the secrecy capacity of wiretap channels, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). It specifically focuses on compound wiretap channels, which are a type of wiretap channel where the eavesdropper's channel is not fixed but can vary over time (cs.CR). The paper also considers the case where the transmitter has channel state information, which is a topic in signal processing (cs.SI). The paper uses a decoder that is robust against randomization, which is a technique commonly used in multimedia security (cs.MM). Finally, the paper also considers the case where there is no channel state information, which is a topic in network security (cs.NI).
